         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s11">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Art auction sales c=
ame to a screeching halt in the second half of 2008=E2=80=94even with <b>Da=
mien Hirst</b>=E2=80=99s $200 million <i>Beautiful Inside My Head Forever</=
i> sale at Sotheby=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94as the panic of the incipient global f=
inancial crisis gripped buyers. The <i>total</i> for all three auction hous=
es in the second half of 2008 was $1.9 billion, less than <i>half</i> of th=
e previous semester=E2=80=99s sales. In the first half of 2009, despite the=
 record total for the <b>Yves-Saint Laurent</b>-<b>Pierre Berg=C3=A9</b> sa=
le that went for around $525 million at Christie=E2=80=99s, the auction mar=
ket fell another 25 percent as banks tumbled. In the second half of 2009, t=
he market pulled back <i>another</i> 14 percent, to reach a generational lo=
w of $1.3 billion in auction sales. <br/><br/>From there, the market crept =
up in its unique rhythm of strong first half and
not-as-strong second half. From the first half of 2010 to the first half of=
 2015, sales rose steadily. The total was $2.9 billion in the first half of=
 2010; by the first half of 2015, sales had reached $5.1 billion. That=E2=
=80=99s a 78 percent increase. Those were the salad days of the art market,=
 as gratifying as they were unexpected after the depressing pall of 2009.<b=
r/><br/>But those five years of steadily rising sales totals became the tem=
plate for many participants=E2=80=99 expectations about the art market=E2=
=80=94which is a challenge in a sentiment-based market. Instead, the period=
 of 2010 to 2015 was clearly a structural shift in the way we thought about=
 the value of art. It=E2=80=99s also the period when new collectors =E2=80=
=9Cdiscovered=E2=80=9D the art market, with its international circuit of ar=
t fairs and global sense of class formation and participation. The art mark=
et was becoming a place where rich people around the world aspired toward a=
 shared culture. <br/><br/>Although the global
population of ultra-high-net-worth individuals has roughly doubled since 20=
15, the art market has struggled with ups and downs since 2016. (That=E2=80=
=99s when the longstanding pattern of increasing first-half totals seems to=
 have broken.) The market contracted in 2016, recovering somewhat in 2017, =
though the two semesters=E2=80=99 sales totals were almost equal (without <=
b>M.B.S.</b>=E2=80=99s $450 million purchase of <b>Leonardo</b>=E2=80=99s <=
i>Salvator Mundi</i> in November, the familiar pattern would have stood up.=
) The following year, the <b>Rockefeller</b> sale finally pushed the auctio=
n market above  the previous top of 2015 (by around $160 million). In 2018 =
and 2019, it began to look like the old pattern of a stronger first half of=
 the year was going to re-establish itself. <br/><br/>Then came the pandemi=
c, when the growth of an absentee online audience for sales meant the old c=
alendar might be up for serious reconsideration, and the flood of global li=
quidity sent art collectors on a
frenzied buying spree. We saw auction sales rise steadily from $3.3 billion=
 in the first half of 2020 to $5.4 billion in the first half of 2022. That=
=E2=80=99s an impressive 62 percent rise, especially notable considering th=
e 2020 numbers had been around the 2017 level. <br/><br/>I=E2=80=99ve point=
ed out previously that we saw pretty much the same pattern after 2018=E2=80=
=99s peak that we=E2=80=99ve seen over the last two years. History in the a=
rt market doesn=E2=80=99t even rhyme; it often repeats. <br/><br/>The histo=
rical data we have from ARTDAI helps us see that the art market is never re=
ally as good (or bad) as it seems. Each of the last three successive cycles=
 have topped out slightly higher than the previous one. At $2.87 billion fo=
r the first half of 2024, we=E2=80=99re already below (on an inflation-adju=
sted basis) the previous market low. If the historical pattern holds, we co=
uld be looking at a season close to $5.5 billion in just a couple of years.=
 <br/></td>
         </tr>
